Suspicious XLOCs

Libraries and fucntions

source("f.R")
library(pheatmap)

Define species and tissue

sp <- "Mouse"
t <- "Liver"

Load data (raw and normalised counts)

rawData <- rawCounts(sp)
normData <- logTransform(loadData(sp))

normData

Let’s select several early liver samples and plot them against average expression (X-Axis) Note the group of genes that have almost zero average expression, but are expressed in Liver.e10.5.4 and Liver.e12.5.3.

samples <- c("Liver.e10.5.1", "Liver.e10.5.4", "Liver.e11.5.2", "Liver.e12.5.3")

as.data.frame(assay(normData, "logcounts")[, samples]) %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "geneId") %>%
  mutate(av = rowMeans(assay(normData, "logcounts"))) %>%
  gather(id, expr, -one_of(c("geneId", "av"))) %>%
  ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x = av, y = expr), size = 0.3, alpha = 0.1) + facet_wrap(~id)

MA plots for the same genes. X-Axis is logorithmise for better resolution. Genes are coloured depending on whether it’s a protein-coding gene or an XLOC.

as.data.frame(assay(normData, "logcounts")[, samples]) %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "geneId") %>%
  mutate(av = rowMeans(assay(normData, "normcounts"))) %>%
  gather(id, expr, -one_of(c("geneId", "av"))) %>%
  mutate(logDif = expr - log2(av + 1)) %>%
  ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x = av, y = logDif, col = grepl("^XLOC", geneId)), size = 0.1) +
  scale_x_log10() + facet_wrap(~id)
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis

The group of strangely behaving genes is best noticeable for the Liver.e10.5.4 sample. The huge skew is due to the fact that we are looking at the very early developmental stages, where most of the genes are not yet expressed. Let’s look at MA plot comparing Liver.e10.5.4 and Liver.e10.5.1 and using non-normalized counts.

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = log2(apply(assay(rawData), 1, mean)), 
                 y = log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.4"]) - log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.1"]), 
                 col = grepl("^XLO", rownames(rawData))), size = 0.5)
## Warning: Removed 29951 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

And that’s how this plot should look like.

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = log2(apply(assay(rawData), 1, mean)), 
                 y = log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.3"]) - log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.1"]), 
                 col = grepl("^XLO", rownames(rawData))), size = 0.5)
## Warning: Removed 31710 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Now let’s select the suspicious genes (very roughly). We also leave only the genes that are expressed in Liver.e10.5.4

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = log2(apply(assay(rawData), 1, mean)), 
                 y = log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.4"]) - log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.1"]), 
                 col = grepl("^XLO", rownames(rawData))), size = 0.5) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 5) + geom_hline(yintercept = 2.5)
## Warning: Removed 29951 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

selGenes <- log2(apply(assay(rawData), 1, mean)) < 5 & 
  (log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.4"]) - log2(assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.1"]) > 2.5) &
  assay(rawData)[, "Liver.e10.5.4"] > 15
selGenes[is.na(selGenes)] <- F

We have selected 1525. Among them 1368 XLOCs and 157 protein coding genes.

Let’s make a heatmap for all Liver samples to refine our selection.

ph <- pheatmap(assay(normData, "logcounts")[selGenes, normData$tissue == "Liver"])

So, it’s easy to spot the two samples, where something went wrong. We also see that bunch of the selected genes is stil expressed in further timepoints and we are interested mostly in the huge cluster in the middle.

clust <- cutree(ph$tree_row, 5)
pheatmap(assay(normData, "logcounts")[selGenes, normData$tissue == "Liver"], 
         annotation_row = data.frame(row.names = names(clust), clust = clust))

Now we can take only the genes from this huge cluster.

selGenes[names(clust)[clust != 1]] <- F

Now we have 1322: 1227 XLOCs and 95 protein coding genes.

Check where are they expressed.

Brain

assay(normData, "logcounts") %>%
  as.data.frame %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "geneId") %>%
  as.tibble %>%
  filter(selGenes) %>%
  gather(id, expr, -(geneId)) %>%
  left_join(colData(normData) %>% 
              as.data.frame() %>%
              rownames_to_column(var = "id"), by = "id") %>%
  filter(tissue == "Brain") %>%
  ggplot() + geom_histogram(aes(x = expr)) + facet_wrap(~id)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
